data.title: Jools Holland on Paula Yates, Royalty and New Year's Eve
data.meta_description: Jools is first-name famous, financially comfortable (estimated to be the tenth wealthiest pianist on the planet, worth many millions), well-loved and better-connected than Telecom.
data.text:
Jools Holland’s annual TV shindig has made him everyone’s favourite New Year host. So when Event was invited to help him see in 2015 with Ed Sheeran, Ellie Goulding and a late-night rabble of the coolest stars, there was only one response. HOOTENANNY!

Amid the musical maelstrom that is the rehearsal for Jools’ Annual Hootenanny, BBC2’s traditional New Year’s Eve spectacular, the show’s presenter perches at a piano with just one thought on his mind… mince pies.

A consignment of 80 Yuletide tartlets is due to be delivered to the studio in Maidstone, Kent, from Clarke’s in Kensington, London, ‘purveyors of the poshest seasonal pastries’ according to the loquacious Holland, and he is excited about their imminent arrival.

‘One for all the musicians and crew,’ he says, then remembers his role in the proceedings. ‘I, of course, have two.’

Holland is an extravagantly gifted pianist and a charming communicator, somewhere between Ray Charles and Prince Charles.

‘I quite like that,’ he says in his distinctive nasal voice and curious Edwardian syntax.

‘I shall henceforth introduce myself with those very words.’

Quiet and contained, in jeans, jumper and square spectacles, Holland watches the unfurling Hootenanny pageantry with a small smile and the faraway air of a fellow mentally alphabetising his Corgi car collection.

Shortly, in a flurry of superlatives, flamboyant body language and bonhomie, Holland will emerge from his dressing room as the bespoke-suited butterfly we have come to know as the name below the Later… logo.

Later… recently concluded its 45th series and this will be Hootenanny number 21.

The show is an institution that musicians from all over the globe clamour to appear on.

Even U2 recently overcame their wariness of live television to give a powerful performance of the kind rarely seen on early-evening TV.

And the Annual Hootenanny is as much of a New Year’s Eve fixture as a chilly visit to Trafalgar Square ever was.

It provides a soundtrack to our Hogmanay parties, the inspiration for irresponsible drinking games and even musical solace for those who ‘don’t do New Year’.

Holland, 56, agrees that Later... sits at the opposite end of the spectrum to The X Factor, although concedes that Simon Cowell probably has ‘a good ear. I must have a look at it the next time I see him,’ he smirks.

Playing the joker is Holland’s default setting, with a flippant quip, or a surreal monologue, when a more earnest response might be required.

He will wax philosophical about the unifying power of music and the circular nature of life, but is happier speculating upon burning questions like whether it is appropriate for Madonna to still be presenting her bare breasts to the world.

‘It depends on circumstance,’ he begins, thoughtfully.

‘If it was just me and Madonna on a bus or, say, in my shed then I might possibly encourage her.

'I don’t really have any political opinions as I limit the scope of my interests to music.

'The only thing I have noticed is that Nigel Farage is a bit of a medieval type. I have been asked to appear on Question Time but I don’t think I’m qualified to give any answers. I’m much better with questions.’

Then he changes tack, his attention span being slight and scattergun, and ponders One Direction’s future.

‘In folk or blues you can become legendary and remain so for years but in pop music you live or die by a haircut,’ he muses.

‘Your audience chuck you away – you’re disposable. So I have the utmost admiration for One Direction because they’re frontline warriors.’

Back at the Hootenanny rehearsal there are fake stars on the ceiling and real stars on the studio floor: Ed Sheeran adjusts his guitar effects in preparation for a run-through of his duet with the host; Ellie Goulding breezes past humming Michael Jackson’s Blame It On The Boogie, which she is due to try out shortly, while Memphis soul man William Bell attempts once more to remember the lyrics to Pharrell Williams’ Happy.

Sundry Scotch Guards saunter through in civvies clutching inert bagpipes. Soon they will produce a sound loud enough to stir the Loch Ness Monster from its watery lair.

Hootenanny regulars, the pipers have traditionally hit their stride as the studio clock strikes midnight, infusing the air with their uplifting melodies and melancholy drones.

There are those who remain impervious to the charms of Hootenanny and Holland himself, but the dapper host, outwardly at least, doesn’t give a hoot.

Jools is first-name famous, financially comfortable (estimated to be the tenth wealthiest pianist on the planet, worth many millions, the result of a lucrative TV contract and a full, handsomely paid concert schedule), well-loved and better-connected than Telecom.

He is a good friend of Prince Charles. Holland went to Charles and Camilla’s wedding in 2005 and in turn invited the Royal couple to his own nuptials the same year. (‘But he was away somewhere,’ Holland explains. ‘Although I had it when everyone was on holiday to give people an excuse for not coming.’)

During their work for the Prince’s Trust has Holland observed Charles’s taste in music?

‘He quite likes opera,’ nods Holland. And when he went to collect his OBE from the Queen in 2003, did Jools let slip he was pals with her eldest?

‘I don’t think you speak unless you’re spoken to,’ he allows cautiously, then checks himself. ‘And I’m afraid I couldn’t possibly share what we did speak about!’

That evening, Holland returns to his day job: leading a big band and pounding his piano, tonight royally entertaining the good people of Brighton.

The rocking Rhythm & Blues Orchestra is augmented by guest vocals from Rumer, Ruby Turner and a magnificently melodramatic Marc Almond.

But it’s not all high camp and knees-up nostalgia. Holland delivers a song, Dead Hosts Welcome, written with New Orleans great Dr John, which is mesmerising, transforming a conservative concrete concert hall into a mysterious Mississippi steamboat.

‘Music is a universal language,’ Holland says, unashamed by the cliché.

‘We were playing for the world leaders at the G8 summit and we started the intro to All You Need Is Love.

'Jacques Chirac stood up because he thought we were playing the French National anthem, then they all got up, realised it was a pop song and had to start dancing. But it’s better to have world leaders dancing together than having a row, so music is a great leveller.’

Julian Miles Holland grew up poor in south-east London.

‘There was a distinct lack of money – we were poor in that sense.

'We did all live in one room at one point and there wasn’t any electricity, but we always entertained each other, so in that respect we were rich.’

He learned the basics of his beloved boogie-woogie aged eight by watching his Uncle David play his grandmother’s upright in her Charlton front parlour, then having practised diligently young Jools plied his ivory-tickling trade in the dockers’ pubs of the East End.

In 1974, by then ‘a long-haired greaser with dirty fingernails’, he formed Squeeze with songwriting schoolfriends Glenn Tilbrook and Chris Difford (staying until 1981) and recorded a sparkling set of pop singles including Cool For Cats, Up The Junction and Another Nail In My Heart, modern-day standards.

His subsequent solo career, hampered by a singing voice that could strip enamel from teeth, was rescued by an offer of TV work from the producers of a chaotic yet compulsive youth magazine show called The Tube on Channel 4. Holland fronted the programme with Paula Yates.

He memorably swore during an early evening trailer (‘be there or be ungroovy f******’), shocked the nation and got suspended. The plug was pulled on The Tube soon after.

‘Everyone swears on air now but I don’t,’ he says seriously. ‘I’d sincerely like to apologise for having offended anyone when I did. It was a slip of the tongue, a moment of madness.’

Holland’s friendship with Yates remains special to him; he played piano at her funeral in 2000.

‘When you’re young you don’t realise you’ve met a unique person and that you probably won’t meet many people like that in your life, but she was a one-off.

'She had that great knack of giving the impression she couldn’t care less.

'Of course, underneath it all she did.’

A friend of Yates once said ‘Paula was so confident and sexy, she could flirt with a door.’

‘That’s right,’ Holland says softly.

‘And she would make the door fall in love with her.’

As she spiralled into addiction, did Holland feel he could have helped?

'Once alcohol or drugs have got a grip it’s pretty hard,’ he says, turning sombre.

‘It was the same with Amy Winehouse. You think you might have been able to do something but at the time you were probably unable to or your help wasn’t wanted.’

Forty-eight hours after the Hootenanny rehearsal, Holland is on the road again.

But no ordinary road. It is the M5 into Exeter, where Holland was involved in a life-threatening and life-changing car crash, after a 1987 show in Plymouth.

‘I feel a lot safer driving into Plymouth than out, put it that way,’ he says vaguely.

But it was a pivotal moment for Holland. Also in the party was Christabel McEwen, now his wife.

However, at the time of the collision, she was his mistress and the accident brought their affair to light, effectively ending Holland’s partnership with Mary Leahy, mother of his children Rosie and George, now 29 and 30.

Holland and sculptor McEwen, daughter of artist Rory McEwen, had a child, Mabel Ray, in 1990, and she now sings with her father’s orchestra.

McEwan was previously married to Edward Lambton, 7th Earl Of Durham, with whom she had a son Fred, Viscount Lambton. Was it a comedown for Holland’s wife to wed a commoner?

‘It would be hard for anyone to marry me without believing it some kind of comedown,’ says Holland diplomatically.

He continues to straddle the class divide ‘taking people on face value, regardless of background’ mixing with toffs and tinkers alike.

Holland lives in Blackheath, south-east London, where his Helicon Mountain recording studio was built to his design and inspired by Portmeirion, setting for Sixties TV series The Prisoner, and from which Holland has derived much of his personal style.

He has built a second home in the 14th Century ruins of Cooling Castle in Kent.

Holland may not be stadium-rock-star rich but he is a close friend of any entertainment deity you care to mention. In his 2007 autobiography, Barefaced Lies And Boogie-Woogie Boasts, he recounts an afternoon spent with George Harrison and Bob Dylan at the late Beatle’s Henley-on-Thames home watching George Formby films. This is the world Holland inhabits.

He has been a guest on Top Gear.

‘It wasn’t much of a lap but in my defence I didn’t realise how shabby the car was.’

And, bookies take note, when asked outright he refuses to discount a rug-cutting turn on Strictly Come Dancing.

‘I couldn’t possibly answer a hypothetical question like that,’ he says adopting the tone of a pressurised politician ‘I’m not known for my dancing and am not a frequenter of the disco. But in the right circumstance I’m unstoppable.’

Enquire how Holland intends to spend New Year’s Eve and he’ll reply, ‘Why, I shall be at the Hootenanny of course!’ loathe to let daylight in upon magic. We nod knowingly.

He is momentarily fascinated by the fact that he has now been a celebrity for longer than he hasn’t been one.

‘I’ve never really thought about it like that,’ he confesses.

‘Boogie-woogie has been very good to me. The originators and inventors of the form had a pretty horrid time but I’ve had a really great time, so I have them to give credit to them for my good fortune.’

And this Christmas, he added to his considerable fortune by appearing in a televised advert for the supermarket Aldi. Asked how he can justify such crass commercialism, Holland circuitously returns to the subject of mince pies.

‘The whole band are in the advert, 20 people, so that’s a good thing for everybody,’ he explains.

‘But should you be inclined to study the advert closely you will notice that the mince pies on top of the piano have had more time and attention lavished on them in hair and make up than any us.

'They were the best looked-after pies in the business – covered in varnish!'

We’re back to trivia. Holland has heard that hallucinogenic mushrooms have been found in the grounds of Buckingham Palace and is discreetly thrilled.

‘Very exciting news,’ he enthuses. ‘Alan Titchmarsh found them – how very like him. What is puzzling me is how did he know what they were?

'His knowledge of magic mushrooms must be astounding. They were a natural phenomenon, were they? Or should we suspect something more sinister?’

He chuckles at the idea of Prince Harry making festive mischief in his grandparents’ garden.

‘Anyway,’ the pianist by Royal appointment decides, ‘it should cheer their New Year up no end.’

‘Jools Holland’s Annual Hootenanny’ is on BBC2 from 11.20pm, New Year’s Eve.

‘Sirens of Song’ by Jools Holland & his Rhythm & Blues Orchestra is out now, joolsholland.com
